  "prompt": "America is divided into how many classes of people?",
  "response": "The classification of people in America can vary based on different criteria such as socioeconomic status, race, ethnicity, or other demographic factors. Commonly, socioeconomic status is divided into classes such as:\n\n1. **Upper Class**: This group includes individuals with significant wealth, high incomes, and substantial assets. They often have influential social and economic power.\n\n2. **Middle Class**: Typically includes individuals with moderate to high incomes who may own homes, have savings, and possess college or advanced degrees. This class is often further subdivided into upper-middle and lower-middle classes.\n\n3. **Working Class**: Individuals in this class usually have lower incomes compared to the middle class, often work in manual or blue-collar jobs, and may have less financial security.\n\n4. **Lower Class**: This group includes individuals with low incomes, limited job opportunities, and may rely on government assistance. They often face economic hardship and instability.\n\nThese classifications can overlap and are influenced by a wide range of factors. Other classifications such as race, ethnicity, education level, and geographic location also play significant roles in the social structure of America.",
